    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">1. Is Ahimsa the most important virtue in Hinduism?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>Ahimsa is described as "Paramo Dharma" (supreme dharma) in the Mahabharata (Anushasana Parva 115.1). However, Hindu philosophy recognises that dharma is contextual — what is appropriate varies by role, circumstance, and stage of life. For a Kshatriya protecting the innocent, righteous force may be more dharmic than non-resistance.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">2. Why did Krishna support war if Ahimsa is supreme?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>Krishna supported the Kurukshetra war because it was a dharmic necessity. The Kauravas had committed multiple grave adharmas. Allowing tyranny to continue unchecked would have caused far greater suffering than the battle. Krishna's teaching is that Ahimsa at the level of the soul (which is indestructible) is absolute; but at the level of social and political action, righteous force to protect the innocent is itself dharma.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">3. Does Hinduism support vegetarianism?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>Many Hindu scriptures and traditions advocate vegetarianism as the highest expression of Ahimsa. The Manusmriti, Bhagavata Purana, and many Vaishnava texts strongly encourage vegetarian diet. However, Hinduism is diverse — many traditions, particularly in coastal and tribal areas, have different dietary practices. The Bhagavad Gita (17.8-10) describes food in terms of gunas rather than strict vegetarianism.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">4. What is the difference between Ahimsa and pacifism?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>Ahimsa in Hindu philosophy is not the same as absolute pacifism. Pacifism refuses violence under all circumstances. Hindu Ahimsa recognises that sometimes protective force is the most dharmic action — as when a soldier protects civilians, or a parent protects a child. The distinction lies in motivation, proportionality, and the absence of hatred.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">5. How did Gandhi interpret Ahimsa?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>Mahatma Gandhi elevated Ahimsa into a complete political and spiritual philosophy of non-violent resistance. He drew primarily from the Gita and the Jain tradition. However, Gandhi's interpretation was selective — he emphasised absolute non-violence in ways that go beyond what the Gita itself teaches. The Gita's Ahimsa is situational and dharmic; Gandhi's was more absolute.</p></div>
</div>

